President Reagan, reacting toCanadian concerns, today announced he will seek 2.5 billiondlrs over five years to combat acid rain.    The announcement said the administration will request fromCongress 500 mln dlrs in each of the next two fiscal years tofund innovative projects to control smokestack emissions --blamed for acid rain that has killed fish and trees in easternCanada.    White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said theadministration had asked for 350 mln dlrs but that Ottawa hadregistered concern about the level of funding.    He said the announcement was "obviously related" to anApril-5-6 summit meeting in Ottawa between Reagan and CanadianPrime Minister Brian Mulroney.    Reagan said that in addition to committing government moneyindustry would be encouraged to invest a greatwer or equalamount to promote new technologies to cut air pollution.    The announcement said an advisory panel, including stategovernmments and the canadian government, would advise onfunding and selection of polllution control projects.    Further, a presidential task force on regulatory reliefwould examine the effect of federal, state and localregulations on deployment of new emission control technologies. Reuter&#3;